{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01RLSbrhVmv5JTCGGvjb9FvY","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a comprehensive understanding of:\n1. The current iteration 26 failures (16 generated-file failures, 0 real-file failures)\n2. The current implementation (complex multi-stage pipeline)\n3. Previous iteration history and progression (from 16.7% to current 85.6% combined / 100% real)\n4. What has been tried (vocabulary corroboration, dictionary-guided OCR repair, candidate-relative position, etc.)\n\nLet me analyze the 6 failure patterns and design fixes.\n\nKey observations:\n- All 16 failures are generated files, 0 real files affected\n- Real file accuracy is 100% (11/11)\n\n\n- Combined accuracy is 85.6%\n\nThe failures cluster into 6 patterns: spillover corruption at page starts (5 cases), heavy digit corruption (2), partial corruption with wrong selection (3), section header issues (3), multi-line titles (1), and mid-recipe page problems (2). For the spillover pattern, the hard filter already catches the corrupted marker, but the actual title gets buried or lost entirely—I need to look deeper into the page when the spillover indicator appears.\n\nThe digit corruption cases are puzzling because iteration 24 supposedly added dictionary-guided OCR repair to handle exactly this scenario, yet these same failures are still appearing. The combined accuracy metrics across iterations suggest something regressed or the repair isn't catching these particular malformed words.\n\nI'm wondering if the issue is that common words like \"with\" might not actually be in the food dictionary—the repair function can only fix what it can match against, so if it's looking for \"w1th\" and trying substitutions, it might fail if the dictionary is too specialized and doesn't include basic English words that happen to appear in recipe titles.\n\nFor Pattern B, I could either expand the repair logic to handle frequent non-food words, apply a more aggressive digit-to-letter substitution for titles specifically, or just be more lenient with position-0 candidates that show digit corruption. Pattern C seems to be a similar issue where the title corruption is bad enough that the extractor skips it entirely and grabs body text instead.\n\nLooking at Pattern D more carefully, I'm noticing that the section header cases I thought were fixed in iteration 24 are actually still failing—the extractor is returning body text or empty results even though the title is clearly on line 3. The candidate-relative position bonus and first-after-preamble bonus aren't strong enough to override the embedding scores, so I need to either strengthen those bonuses or reconsider the ranking logic entirely.\n\nChecking the iteration progression, I see that iteration 25 hit 100% on real cases but iteration 26 dropped to 85.6% combined, which suggests the generated file failures are dragging down the score. The fundamental problem is that the extractor is being too cautious about position-0 and position-1 candidates when they have any corruption, and too quick to fall back to body text or return nothing. What I really need is a stronger principle: if a line is in the title position—the first non-filtered line—it should get very strong preference unless there's clear evidence it's not a title.\n\nPattern E involves a multi-line title that's getting cut off...\n\nthe issue is that the caps coalescing logic won't merge consecutive lines if the second line is flagged as a section label, even when it's actually part of the title. So `VEGETABLES` blocks the merge even though it should be combined with `LEMON HERB ROASTED`. The fix is to relax that blocking condition when the preceding line looks incomplete or fragmented.\n\nFor Pattern F, the title-absent detection isn't catching cases where the page starts with body text rather than ingredients, like in the Mushroom Risotto example where it picks up the next recipe's title instead. I need to strengthen that heuristic.\n\nMy improvement plan focuses on three main areas: expanding the OCR repair dictionary to handle more cooking terms and common English words beyond just food items, boosting the position-0 preference so early candidates with minor corruption are still favored if they look structurally sound, and refining the title-absent detection to better handle pages that start mid-recipe with body text.\n\nI should also reconsider whether the section label blocking is a real issue or if it's just a symptom of the deeper OCR and position-preference problems. The feedback warns against incremental changes when there's a fundamental design flaw, so I'm thinking the core issue might be that OCR repair is too conservative.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":16527,"cache_read_input_tokens":64730,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":16527},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"d80e2ded-f7a7-46bb-8be0-f1bcb73047ba","uuid":"7913c461-dd54-40b4-bdc6-7d90c97175a4"}
